k for its Clinical Reference Groups (CRFs), which exist to provide expert advice to NHS England on specialised services. A new CRF for adult gender identity services was established in September 2016. Membership of the group includes those using NHS services for transgender people and clinicians and the Chair was appointed following an open recruitment process. The CRF has been asked to deliver draft service specifications for adult gender identity services in January 2017. These will be informed by a consideration of the Women and Equalities Committee’s findings and recommendations and by a process of stakeholder engagement and public consultation. In October 2016, NHS England gave notice to all current providers of gender identity services in England that their contracts would be terminated in 2017 and that they will run an open national procurement process to identify providers to deliver against new contracts. Prospective bidders will be required to demonstrate compliance with the new service specifications, once agreed.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood","55059 ; 55061 ; 55062","2016-12-06T16:33:10.4Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647198/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647198/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647198/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-28","Gender Recognition","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, with reference to pages 18 and 19 of the Government response to the First Report from the Women and Equalities Committee, Session 2015-16, on Transgender Equality, Cm 9301, published in July 2016, what steps NHS England has taken to strengthen governance arrangements to review within six months NHS compliance with the Equality Act 2010 in respect of services for transgender people.","false","Biography information for Mrs Maria Miller","Basingstoke","Mrs Maria Miller","55063"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647199","Department of Health","false","2016-12-01","<p>NHS England has advised that, whilst it recognises that bisphosphonates may have benefits for some women in preventing secondary breast cancer, their provision is a matter for clinical commissioning groups.</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>Bisphosphonates are not licensed for the treatment or prevention of secondary breast cancer. However, clinicians can prescribe bisphosphonates ‘off-license’ subject to any local funding policies if they consider them to be clinically appropriate for an individual, as current prescribing arrangements allow off-license drugs that are found to have new uses to be prescribed to patients.</p><p> </p><p>Prescribing decisions are for clinicians taking into account their patients’ individual clinical circumstances. There is no legal or regulatory barrier to the funding or prescribing of drugs off-license. Prescribing in this way is part of normal every day clinical practice and offers benefits to a great number of patients.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-12-01T09:26:08.143Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647199/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647199/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647199/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-28","Breast Cancer: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps NHS England is taking to increase bisphosphonates prescription for the prevention of secondary breast cancer; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","55067"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647200","Department of Health","false","2016-12-05","<p>My Rt. hon. Friend the Secretary of State for Health meets NHS England and NHS Improvement on a weekly basis to discuss National Health Service performance at a local level.</p><p> </p><p>It is the responsibility of NHS Trust Boards, their commissioners and regulators, and of the clinicians who work at trusts, to ensure service delivery meets the required performance standards.</p><p> </p><p>A search of the Department’s Ministerial correspondence database has identified 10 items of correspondence received since 1 June 2016 relating to the Pennine Acute Hospitals NHS Trust. This includes letters from members of the public about their experience of care and treatment at the Trust, and Regulation 28 Reports to Prevent Future Deaths following inquests held into the deaths of patients who received care and treatment from the Trust.</p><p> </p><p>This figure represents correspondence received by the Department’s Ministerial correspondence unit only.</p><p> </p><p>In September 2016, the Department replied to the hon. Member for Blackley and Broughton’s (Graham Stringer) Parliamentary Question <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-questions-answers/?page=1&amp;max=20&amp;questiontype=AllQuestions&amp;house=commons%2clords&amp;uin=44138" target="_blank">44138</a> about avoidable deaths at Pennine Acute Hospitals NHS Trust.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-12-05T15:42:15.403Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647200/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647200/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647200/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-28","Pennine Acute Hospitals NHS Trust","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what recent representations he has received on the performance of the Pennine Acute Trust; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","55028"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647201","Department of Health","false","2016-12-01","<p>Information is not collected centrally on the conditions for which medicines are prescribed. Bisphosphonates are primarily used to prevent or treat osteoporosis.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-12-01T13:45:32.453Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647201/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647201/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647201/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-28","Breast Cancer: Drugs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the number of prescriptions issued for bisphosphonates to prevent secondary breast cancer in each year that figures are available; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Mr Jim Cunningham","Coventry South","Mr Jim Cunningham","55068"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647202","Department of Health","false","2016-12-06","<p>The Department does not hold data on the amounts collected as fees from overseas private patients.</p><p> </p><p>Since 2013-14, the Department has been collecting data on the amount invoiced by National Health Service trusts and NHS foundation trusts, together with amounts recovered and written off for NHS treatment of overseas patients entitled to be treated as NHS patients under the NHS (Charges to Overseas Visitors) Regulations 2015.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-12-06T14:30:17.853Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647202/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647202/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647202/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-28","NHS Trusts: Private Patients","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much in fees from overseas private patients was (a) collected by and (b) remain outstanding to NHS trusts in each of the last five years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","55034"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647203","Department of Health","false","2016-12-06","<p>The Government’s expectation is that the National Health Service will deliver financial balance in each year of the current Spending Review period (2016-17 to 2020-21). This expectation is made clear in the Government’s mandate to NHS England for 2016-17 and the mandate is produced annually.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-12-06T11:26:06.113Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647203/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647203/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647203/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-28","NHS: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the potential surplus or deficit in the NHS Provider sector in each of the next five years.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","55032"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647204","Department of Health","false","2016-12-06","<p>I refer to the answer I gave on 22 November 2016 to the hon. Member for Liverpool, Wavertree (Luciana Berger) to Question <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-11-17/53618/" target="_blank">53618</a>.</p>","Oxford West and Abingdon","Nicola Blackwood",,"2016-12-06T16:34:22.617Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647204/answer","Biography information for Baroness Blackwood of North Oxford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647204/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647204/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-28","Mental Health Services: Children","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how many young people aged 17 or under of each age were treated in adult mental health wards in 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Norman Lamb","North Norfolk","Norman Lamb","55042"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647205","Department of Health","false","2016-12-01","<p>Local National Health Service organisations are responsible for making their own arrangements for minimising the number of people missing or cancelling ophthalmology appointments.</p><p> </p><p>The Department, in conjunction with behavioural scientists at Imperial College, conducted randomised controlled trials at Barts Hospitals NHS Trust looking at the content of the most effective text message reminder. The results were published in an online academic journal in September 2015<sup>1</sup> and summarised on the Department’s website in January 2016<sup>2</sup>.</p><p><sup>1</sup> <a href="http://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0137306" target="_blank">http://journals.plos.org/plosone/article?id=10.1371/journal.pone.0137306</a></p><p><sup> </sup><sup>2</sup> <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/reducing-missed-hospital-appointments-using-text-messages" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/reducing-missed-hospital-appointments-using-text-messages</a></p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-12-01T09:04:12.713Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647205/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647205/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647205/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-28","Ophthalmology","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what steps he is taking to decrease the number of people missing or cancelling ophthalmology appointments.","false","Biography information for Sir Hugo Swire","East Devon","Sir Hugo Swire","55012"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647206","Department of Health","false","2016-12-06","<p>The vast majority of income and costs of National Health Service budgets are denominated in pounds sterling. There are a number of reasons for changes in NHS finances, and, as ever, specifically identifying the impact of exchange rate changes is not routinely undertaken.</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-12-06T11:25:17.09Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647206/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647206/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647206/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-28","NHS: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what effect recent changes in the rate of sterling have had on the finances of the NHS.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","55029"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647207","Department of Health","false","2016-12-06","<p>The Sustainability and Transformation Plans (STPs) submitted on 21 October 2016 demonstrate tangible progress in addressing this financial gap referred to in the NHS Five Year Forward View.</p><p> </p><p>Providers and commissioners are currently in the process of agreeing two-year operating plans and contracts for financial years 2017-19. Once agreed, these plans will form the basis for the first two years of implementation of the STPs.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat",,"2016-12-06T14:24:37.157Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647207/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647207/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647207/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-28","NHS: Reorganisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what estimate he has made of the number of sustainability and transformation plans that he has received which will achieve the savings targets identified.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","55035"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647208","Department of Health","false","2016-12-05","<p>The income recorded from National Health Service providers from private patients for the past five years is in the table below. Any surplus generated from the treatment of private patients is reinvested by the provider for the benefit of NHS patients.</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>2011-12 £000s</p></td><td><p>2012-13 £000s</p></td><td><p>2013-14 £000s</p></td><td><p>2014-15 £000s</p></td><td><p>2015-16 £000s</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>454,062</p></td><td><p>478,761</p></td><td><p>501,708</p></td><td><p>526,138</p></td><td><p>558,194</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p>For the sake of consistency the figures for 2011-12 and 2012-13 include private patient income from primary care trust (PCT) providers. All PCTs ceased providing healthcare from 2013-14.</p><p> </p><p>The Department does not collect figures for outstanding fees from private patients.</p><p> </p><p><em>Source:</em> Department of Health Annual Report and Accounts 2011-2016</p>","Ludlow","Mr Philip Dunne",,"2016-12-05T15:35:36.497Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647208/answer","Biography information for Mr Philip Dunne","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647208/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647208/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-28","NHS Trusts: Private Patients","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, how much in fees from private patients (a) was collected by and (b) remain outstanding to NHS trusts in each of the last five years for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","55033"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647209","Department of Health","false","2016-12-01","<p>Local service leaders in every part of England have worked together to produce shared Sustainability and Transformation Plans (STPs) to transform health and care in the communities they serve, and to agree how to spend increasing investment in the National Health Service. Some of the 44 STPs feature plans to develop accountable care organisations, the characteristics of which will depend on local service design.</p><p> </p><p>Through the new care models programme, the Five Year Forward View arms-length bodies are helping local partnerships develop and implement new care models, two of which are population-health models - Multispecialty Community Providers (MCPs) and Integrated Primary and Acute Care Systems (PACS). As these care models develop, the partner organisations are expected to take on shared accountability for the health and care of the populations they serve.</p><p> </p><p>By sharing accountability, and providing services that best meet the needs of their local populations, MCPs and PACS are expected to deliver much greater integration between primary and acute care; physical and mental health; health and social care; improving health outcomes; and the quality, accessibility, and efficiency of local services. Where this involves substantial service reconfiguration, local areas will be expected to consult patients and the public in the normal way.</p><p> </p><p>The new care models programme has recently published the MCP and PACS frameworks, which set out further the emerging care models and their benefits, and examples of best practice that others can implement. National MCP and PACS contracts are being developed to underpin these care models. Existing requirements on the NHS around commissioning and the procurement of services, including services provided by the independent sector, will continue to apply to new care models.</p>","Warrington South","David Mowat","55082 ; 55083 ; 55085","2016-12-01T14:42:52.35Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647209/answer","Biography information for David Mowat","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647209/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647209/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-28","Accountable Care Organisations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health, what his policy is on the introduction of accountable care organisations.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","55081"
