"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647294","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-06","<p>The Department does not publish data on the number of Personal Independence Payment assessments cancelled and re-arranged. To check the validity of the data would incur disproportionate cost.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-12-06T17:23:22.773Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647294/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647294/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647294/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-11-28","Personal Independence Payment: South West","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many appointments for claimants applying for personal independence payments have been rearranged or cancelled at the request of a person other than the claimant in (a) Plymouth and (b) the South West in the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Johnny Mercer","Plymouth, Moor View","Johnny Mercer","55127"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647295","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-01","<p>The figures requested are in the table below:</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p><strong>Households classified as under-occupying: East Ham constituency, 2013-2016</strong></p><p><em> </em></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>August 2013</strong></p></td><td><p>750</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>August 2014</strong></p></td><td><p>650</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>August 2015</strong></p></td><td><p>600</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>August 2016</strong></p></td><td><p>560</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong>Households classified as under-occupying: London Borough of Newham, 2013-2016</strong></p><p><em> </em></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>August 2013</strong></p></td><td><p>2,140</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>August 2014</strong></p></td><td><p>1,850</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>August 2015</strong></p></td><td><p>1,680</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>August 2016</strong></p></td><td><p>1,570</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p><strong>Households classified as under-occupying: Greater London, 2013-2016</strong></p><p><em>Thousands</em></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>August 2013</strong></p></td><td><p>55.3</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>August 2014</strong></p></td><td><p>48.2</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>August 2015</strong></p></td><td><p>45.1</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>August 2016</strong></p></td><td><p>41.3</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p> </p><p><strong>Notes:</strong></p><ol><li><em>Constituency and Local Authority figures have been rounded to the nearest ten, and regional figures have been rounded to the nearest hundred.</em></li><li><em>Figures are numbers of households receiving Housing Benefit with a spare room subsidy deduction. This policy only affects working age households in the social rented sector.</em></li><li><em>Figures have not been provided for August 2012 as the social rented sector spare room subsidy policy did not exist until April 2013.</em></li><li><em>A small number of households now receive their housing support through Universal Credit. The table covers Housing Benefit only as equivalent Universal Credit data are not yet available.</em></li></ol>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2016-12-01T15:23:37.303Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647295/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647295/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647295/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-11-28","Housing Benefit: Social Rented Housing","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people in (a) East Ham constituency, (b) the London Borough of Newham and (c) Greater London have been classified as under-occupying their homes in each year since 2012.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","55231"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647296","HM Treasury","false","2016-12-01","<p>In future, all families - those in receipt of benefits and those supporting themselves solely through work - will be faced with the same sorts of financial considerations when making decisions about having more children. Families will no longer be able to claim additional support through Child Tax Credit (CTC) for third or subsequent children in a family where the child is born on or after 6 April 2017.</p><p> </p><p>However, recognising that some parents or carers are not in the same position to make a choice, the Government has been clear that there would be exceptions for third and subsequent children for certain groups. This includes children who are in kinship care arrangements or born from non-consensual sex.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-12-01T15:58:57.493Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647296/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647296/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647296/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-11-28","Child Tax Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, whether under the proposed limitation of child tax credits to the first two children in a household, a third child in that household with a date of birth after April 2017 would be eligible for child tax credit payment, if the second child were cared for under kinship care arrangements or had been born as a result of non-consensual sex.","false","Biography information for Lucy Powell","Manchester Central","Lucy Powell","55214"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647297","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-01","<p>This Government is committed to action that tackles the root causes of poverty and disadvantage, not just the symptoms. There is clear evidence that work is the best route out of poverty. Working age adults in non-working families are almost four times more likely than those in work to be living on a low income. And the Child Poverty Transitions Report (Jun 2015) found that 74% of poor children in workless families that moved into full employment exited poverty.</p><p>This is why we are reforming the welfare and tax system to support people into work, ensure that work always pays, and to allow people to keep more of what they earn. For the first time ever we are supporting claimants who are in low paid work to increase their earnings and progress in their careers.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-12-01T16:04:51.25Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647297/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647297/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647297/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-11-28","Child Poverty Unit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 25 November 2016 to Question 54256, what steps the Child Poverty Unit is taking to reduce poverty among children living in working households.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","55237"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647298","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-01","<p>The Department for Work and Pensions does not hold sufficiently reliable data on claimant flows into work to answer this question. Benefit claimants are not required to report their destination to Jobcentre Plus when they stop claiming benefit. However, as we roll out Universal Credit, we expect to be able to use Real Time Information (RTI) to track claimant earnings.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-12-01T17:17:05.717Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647298/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647298/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647298/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-11-28","Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people have moved into work from receiving out-of-work benefits in each of the last five years; and how many such people have moved into work with a salary above 60 per cent of median household income in each of those years by year.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","55249"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647299","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-01","<p>The Department for Work and Pensions does not hold sufficiently reliable data on claimant flows into work to answer this question. Benefit claimants are not required to report their destination to Jobcentre Plus when they stop claiming benefit. However, as we roll out Universal Credit, we expect to be able to use Real Time Information (RTI) to track claimant earnings.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-12-01T17:19:49.693Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647299/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647299/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647299/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-11-28","Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people have moved into work and earn above the national minimum wage from receiving out-of-work benefits in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","55250"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647300","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-01","<p>Universal Credit provides us, for the first time, with the opportunity to help people who are in low-paid work to progress. This is the first time that any country has made a significant commitment to supporting people through the welfare system to seek to increase their earnings in work. We are currently at the stage of testing a range of approaches to provide evidence for the development of our future in-work policy. This involves work with individuals – including a large-scale Randomised Control Trial delivered by Jobcentre Plus – and with employers, who play a central role.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-12-01T15:56:06.18Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647300/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647300/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647300/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-11-28","Low Pay","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what steps the Government is taking to enable people in low-paid professions to move into positions with a higher salary.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","55251"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647301","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-01","<p>The information requested is not readily available and could only be provided at disproportionate cost.</p>","East Hampshire","Damian Hinds",,"2016-12-01T15:49:07.2Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647301/answer","Biography information for Mr Damian Hinds","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647301/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647301/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-11-28","Means-tested Benefits: Greater London","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many hardship payments have been issued by his Department to people living in (a) East Ham constituency, (b) the London Borough of Newham and (c) Greater London in each year since 2012.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","55268"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647302","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-12-01","<p>To assist claimants, DWP shares information with HMRC to help identify those Child Tax Credits (CTC) claimants entitled to higher rate CTC because of the Disability Living Allowance (DLA) Child award. The clerical process to do this was not working as intended and resulted in a reduced number of clerical referrals from DWP to HMRC.</p><p> </p><p>Referral volumes are now back in line with expectations and there have been no further issues reported. We remain committed to taking all reasonable steps to make the process more robust.</p><p> </p><p>At the Autumn Statement the Government announced HMRC will put this right for claimants affected this year and claimants will receive a lump sum payment to reflect entitlement since 6 April 2016, and an on-going higher award.</p>","Portsmouth North","Penny Mordaunt",,"2016-12-01T15:43:47.067Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647302/answer","Biography information for Penny Mordaunt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647302/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647302/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2016-11-28","Welfare Tax Credits: Disability","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to paragraph 6.2 of the Autumn Statement 2016, what the reasons were for the error which resulted in families with disabled children not being in receipt of their full tax credit entitlement.","false","Biography information for Frank Field","Birkenhead","Frank Field","55270"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647303","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-06","<p>The Government recognises the important role post offices play in communities across the country, especially in the more remote, rural areas. This is why in our Manifesto we committed to secure the future of 3,000 rural post offices.</p><p> </p><p>Government will have provided nearly £2 billion between 2010 and 2018 to maintain modernise and protect a network of at least 11,500 post offices across the country, which includes funding to invest in rural community branches to improve the customer offer and increase their sustainability.</p><p> </p><p>Through Government’s investment, there over 11,600 post offices in UK and the network is at its most stable in decades.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-12-06T17:13:02.293Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647303/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647303/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647303/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-28","Post Offices: Rural Areas","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps he is taking to support rural post offices.","false","Biography information for Craig Whittaker","Calder Valley","Craig Whittaker","55166"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647304","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-06","<p>Innovate UK’s Chief Executive is responsible for determining the organisation’s staffing level, ensuring it is both affordable and that recruitment controls are observed. The creation of UK Research and Innovation, subject to Parliament, and the announcement at the 2016 Autumn Statement of the Industrial Strategy Challenge Fund, may have an impact on staffing at Innovate UK in due course. The Government will work with the Chief Executive to ensure the organisation is appropriately resourced.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-12-06T16:08:24.6Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647304/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647304/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647304/answer","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647304/answer/previousversion/24142","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-28","Innovate UK: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what plans he has for the future staffing of Innovate UK.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","55186"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647305","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-01","<p>I refer the hon Member to the answer given to the Hon Member for Sheffield, Heeley (Louise Haigh) to question UIN <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2015-12-10/19649/" target="_blank">19649</a> answered on 15 December 2015. No further payments are due to McKinsey for its work on BIS2020.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-12-01T17:12:48.25Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647305/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647305/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647305/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-28","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Reorganisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how much has been paid to McKinsey for its work on the BIS 2020 project; and what further such payments are due.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","55185"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647306","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-06","<p>We are reviewing the current operating model of the Insolvency Service to enable us to further increase our efficiency and effectiveness. This will include an assessment of future staffing requirements.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-12-06T17:16:27.217Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647306/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647306/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647306/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-28","Insolvency Service: Staff","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what plans he has for the future staffing of the Insolvency Service.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","55153"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647308","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2017-01-06","<p>The Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy has no plans to establish an Extended Ministerial Office.</p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2017-01-06T10:46:48.557Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647308/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647308/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647308/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-28","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy: Extended Ministerial Offices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether he plans to establish an extended ministerial office.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","55154"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647309","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-01","<p>The BIS 2020 reform programme was developed to ensure the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills (BIS) was able to deliver efficiency savings while making the Department simpler and better for users. Following the Machinery of Government changes, the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy (BEIS) is considering how best to align the reform agendas of its two predecessor Departments.</p><p> </p><p> </p>","Stourbridge","Margot James",,"2016-12-01T17:15:35.593Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647309/answer","Biography information for Margot James","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647309/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647309/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-28","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills: Reorganisation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, whether the BIS 2020 project is ongoing.","false","Biography information for Clive Lewis","Norwich South","Clive Lewis","55184"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647310","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-06","<p>From 2013–2015, government and its agencies (including Innovate UK and the Research Councils) invested on average over £200m per year in support for low carbon innovation. This included support for identifying, promoting, and developing innovations in the wind and marine sectors, including for the Glasgow-based Offshore Renewable Energy Catapult and Supergen UK Centre for Marine Energy Research.</p><p>From 2016-2021, government has committed to increase the UK’s energy innovation spend, such that by 2021 it will have doubled to over £400m per year. This funding will support innovation across the energy sector in regions across the UK, and details will be set out in due course. Through the new Energy Innovation Board, chaired by Sir Mark Walport, the Department for Business, Energy, and Industrial Strategy will be collaborating with Innovate UK, the Research Councils, and other delivery partners across government, including members of Devolved Administrations, to co-ordinate energy innovation activities.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-12-06T10:57:10.503Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647310/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647310/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647310/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-28","Renewable Energy","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps his Department is taking to identify, promote and develop innovations in (a) wind, (b) wave, (c) tidal and (d) riverflow cold renewables.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","55151"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647311","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-07","<p>The Government does not publish projections of the future use of biomass fuels. Accurate modelling requires knowledge of Government policies beyond this Parliament. In 2011 we published an analysis of the technical potential of various biomass feedstocks which could be available for use in bioenergy. This can be found at:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/48059/1464-aea-2010-uk-and-global-bioenergy-report.pdf" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/48059/1464-aea-2010-uk-and-global-bioenergy-report.pdf</a></p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-12-07T10:31:55.783Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647311/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647311/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647311/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-28","Biofuels","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what estimate the Government has made of the projected use of biomass fuels in each of the next 20 years.","false","Biography information for Dr Paul Monaghan","Caithness, Sutherland and Easter Ross","Dr Paul Monaghan","55150"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647312","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-06","<p><em>The Energy Efficiency (Private Rented Property)(England and Wales) Regulations 2015</em> requires that all landlords of domestic and non-domestic privately rented property in England and Wales ensure that, from 1 April 2018, their properties reach an energy performance rating of at least an E before granting a tenancy to new or existing tenants, unless a prescribed exemption applies.</p><p>Officials are considering the potential impact of the current absence of Green Deal finance from the market on the effective working of the regulations, and whether any changes may be required.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-12-06T15:53:32.717Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647312/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647312/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647312/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-28","Green Deal Scheme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, when he plans to publish a consultation on changes to the Energy Efficiency (Private Rented Property) (England and Wales) Regulations 2015 required as a result of the end of the Green Deal.","false","Biography information for Dr Alan Whitehead","Southampton, Test","Dr Alan Whitehead","55097"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647313","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-06","<p>I refer the hon. Member to the answer I gave my hon. Friend the Member for Montgomeryshire on 1<sup>st</sup> December 2016 to Question <a href="http://www.parliament.uk/business/publications/written-questions-answers-statements/written-question/Commons/2016-11-23/54581/" target="_blank">54581</a>.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-12-06T15:58:25.683Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647313/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647313/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647313/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-28","Energy: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what proportion of Warm Home Discount recipients who are (a) British Gas, (b) EON, (c) nPower, (d) Scottish Power, (e) SSE and (f) Big Six customers overall are on their supplier's variable tariff.","false","Biography information for Dr Alan Whitehead","Southampton, Test","Dr Alan Whitehead","55108"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647314","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-06","<p>Data on customers who are on the Priority Service Register (PSR) is published by Ofgem. However, due to the incompatibility of the data sets, this cannot be linked with the data held by the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy on the type of tariffs customers are on. For this reason, we cannot calculate the proportion of PSR customers who are on standard variable tariffs.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","55107","2016-12-06T15:57:34.637Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647314/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647314/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647314/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-28","Energy: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what proportion of Priority Service Register customers of (a) British Gas, (b) EON, (c) nPower, (d) Scottish Power, (e) SSE and (f) the Big Six energy companies on their supplier's standard variable tariff.","false","Biography information for Dr Alan Whitehead","Southampton, Test","Dr Alan Whitehead","55109"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647315","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-06","<p>Fuel poverty has received Parliamentary scrutiny in Westminster Hall debates held on November 24<sup>th</sup> 2015 and February 6<sup>th</sup> 2016 and in the House of Lords on October 25<sup>th</sup> 2016. Government also published a report setting out annual fuel poverty statistics on June 30<sup>th</sup> 2016.</p><p>The Department recognises the importance of Government holding an annual debate on this topic in Parliament, and will seek to schedule a debate as soon as Parliamentary time allows.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-12-06T15:55:02.283Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647315/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647315/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647315/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-28","Fuel Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, with reference to paragraph 7.5 of the Fuel Poverty Strategy, on what date the first annual fuel poverty debate in Parliament was held; and when the Government plans to timetable the next such debate.","false","Biography information for Dr Alan Whitehead","Southampton, Test","Dr Alan Whitehead","55114"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647316","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-06","<p>The English Housing Survey, from which Fuel Poverty estimates are calculated, does not collect information on whether a surveyed household has an EPC certificate.</p><p>Detailed tables for 2014 fuel poverty statistics for England can be found here:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/fuel-poverty-detailed-tables-2014" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/fuel-poverty-detailed-tables-2014</a>.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2016-12-06T15:54:16.253Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647316/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647316/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647316/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-28","Energy Performance Certificates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, how many fuel poor households are living in properties that have been assessed for an energy performance certificate the result of which has been placed on the register.","false","Biography information for Dr Alan Whitehead","Southampton, Test","Dr Alan Whitehead","55106"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647317","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-06","<p>Data on customers who are on the Priority Service Register (PSR) is published by Ofgem. However, due to the incompatibility of the data sets, this cannot be linked with the data held by the Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy on the type of tariffs customers are on. For this reason, we cannot calculate the proportion of PSR customers who are on standard variable tariffs.</p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman","55109","2016-12-06T15:57:34.59Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647317/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647317/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647317/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-28","Energy: Prices","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what proportion of Priority Service Register customers of (a) British Gas, (b) EON, (c) nPower, (d) Scottish Power, (e) SSE and (f) the Big Six energy companies have been on their supplier's variable tariff for (i) three years or over, (ii) five years or over, (iii) 10 years or over and (iv) 15 years or over.","false","Biography information for Dr Alan Whitehead","Southampton, Test","Dr Alan Whitehead","55107"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647318","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-14","<p>The Autumn Statement (para 3.31) confirmed that additional funding for science and research of £100 million will be provided until 2020-21 to incentivise university collaboration in tech transfer and in working with business. This will support universities working together across England on the commercialisation of research, with the devolved administrations receiving funding through the Barnett formula in the usual way. The funding for England will be allocated by Higher Education Funding Council for England (HEFCE). We are working with HEFCE on options to support these activities. Funding will be allocated through competitive processes and mechanisms, complementing and building on established Higher Education Innovation Funding (HEIF) mechanisms.</p><p> </p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-12-14T17:22:20.113Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647318/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647318/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647318/answer","Orpington","Joseph Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647318/answer/previousversion/24141","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-28","Universities: North of England","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, with reference to paragraph 4.9 of the Government's Northern Powerhouse Strategy, published in November 2016, from which funding streams the £100 million spending to 2020-21 on incentivising university collaboration in tech transfer and working with business will be drawn; and how those funds will be distributed.","false","Biography information for Peter Kyle","Hove","Peter Kyle","55071"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647319","Department for International Trade","false","2016-12-06","Cabinet colleagues regularly discuss a whole range of trade issues with the aim of delivering the best results for the UK.","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2016-12-06T17:37:04.077Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647319/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647319/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647319/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-11-28","EU External Trade","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, whether he has had any discussions with Cabinet colleagues on the potential for the EU having to pay compensation to countries with which it has trade deals as a result of the shrinking of the market when the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","55020"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647320","Department for International Trade","false","2016-12-01","<p>The value of seafood exports from Northern Ireland since 2012 is given in the attached table. Source: HM Revenue and Customs Interactive Regional Trade Statistics database.</p><p> </p>","Wyre Forest","Mark Garnier",,"2016-12-01T17:55:04.483Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647320/answer","Biography information for Mark Garnier","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647320/answer","55069 - Table.docx","55069 - Table.docx","Seafood Exports from NI","Seafood Exports from NI","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647320/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2016-11-28","Seafood: Northern Ireland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what the value was of seafood exports from Northern Ireland in (a) 2012-13, (b) 2013-14, (c) 2014-15 and (d) 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Douglas Chapman","Dunfermline and West Fife","Douglas Chapman","55069"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647321","Department for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","false","2016-12-06","<p>Negotiations on the UK’s exit from the EU will consider all elements of our relationship with Europe including the EU Observatory. The Government continues to focus on achieving the best deal for the UK once we leave the EU.</p>","Orpington","Joseph Johnson",,"2016-12-06T15:52:52.553Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647321/answer","Biography information for Joseph  Johnson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647321/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647321/answer",,,,,"201","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy","2016-11-28","Trade Marks","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Business, Energy and Industrial Strategy, what steps he plans to take to ensure that businesses in the UK continue to benefit from the activities of the EU observatory on trademark protection after the UK leaves the EU.","false","Biography information for Barry Gardiner","Brent North","Barry Gardiner","55037"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647322","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-12-05","We are working closely with the shipping industry to understand the challenges and opportunities that leaving the EU could bring. On 16 November the Secretary of State for Transport held a roundtable with representatives from the sector, attended by Lord Bridges, in order to hear their views. The Department for Exiting the European Union, working with officials across government, continues to undertake a wide range of data analysis covering the entirety of the UK economy. We are looking at over 50 sectors as well as cross-cutting regulatory issues, which will naturally cover the UK shipping industry. This will inform the UK's position for the upcoming negotiations with our EU partners.<p>The UK is an island nation with an outstanding maritime heritage. The maritime sector today is vast, strong and competitive. This is not going to change when we leave the EU.</p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2016-12-05T16:27:17.287Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647322/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647322/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647322/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-11-28","Shipping: UK Trade with EU","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what assessment he has made of the potential effect of the UK leaving the EU Single Market on the UK shipping industry.","false","Biography information for Stephen Gethins","North East Fife","Stephen Gethins","55046"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647323","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-12-05","<p>The Prime Minister has consistently made clear that Parliament will of course be involved in helping to shape the UK’s future as we leave the European Union. That will include a series of debates.<br><br></p><p>The Department for Exiting the European Union is working closely with the Department of Health to build a detailed understanding of how withdrawing from the EU will affect health and social care. <br><br></p><p> </p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2016-12-05T17:05:19.107Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647323/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647323/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647323/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-11-28","Health Services and Social Services","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, if he will make time available for hon. Members to debate the potential effect of the UK leaving the EU on health and social care.","false","Biography information for Justin Madders","Ellesmere Port and Neston","Justin Madders","55030"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647324","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-12-06","<p>We fully recognise the UK insurance industry’s valuable contribution to our economy. As a Commons report found last year, the Financial and Insurance Services Sector contributed £124.4bn to the UK economy, and represented 8% of GVA.</p><p>The UK insurance industry is the largest in the world, and manages over £1.9 trillion of investments.</p><p>The industry is underpinned by a number of factors including a pool of liquidity in the UK and significant expertise built up over decades.</p><p>We have held a number of meetings with the insurance industry and DExEU and HMT recently held a roundtable with representatives of the financial services industry including leading insurers to ensure all views are reflected in our analysis of the options for the UK’s withdrawal from the European Union.</p><p>The government is committed to ensuring the UK remains a world leader in this area.</p><p> </p>","Worcester","Mr Robin Walker",,"2016-12-06T15:17:24.93Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647324/answer","Biography information for Mr Robin Walker","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647324/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647324/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-11-28","Insurance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, if he will take steps to ensure that negotiations on the UK's exit from the EU will support the UK's insurance industry so that it remains a significant UK export industry.","false","Biography information for Mr Chris Leslie","Nottingham East","Chris Leslie","55039"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647325","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-12-05","<p>The Department for Exiting the European Union is properly resourced. The Autumn Statement announced additional funding of up to £51m in 2016-17 and up to £94m p.a. from 2017-18 until the UK’s exit is complete. The Department for Exiting the European Union now has just over 300 staff, and is growing fast.</p><p>The full budget for the Department will be presented to Parliament at the Supplementary Estimate in the New Year as is standard practice.</p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2016-12-05T16:25:44.513Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647325/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647325/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647325/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-11-28","Department for Exiting the European Union: Recruitment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, what his Department's budget is for hiring staff needed to facilitate the negotiations to leave the EU in 2016-17.","false","Biography information for Jonathan Edwards","Carmarthen East and Dinefwr","Jonathan Edwards","55266"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647326","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-12-01","<p>The Government has set out the timetable for triggering Article 50 by the end of March 2017 and that timetable has not changed.</p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones",,"2016-12-01T15:24:21.42Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647326/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647326/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647326/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-11-28","Brexit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, whether his policy is to trigger Article 50 by 31 March 2017.","false","Biography information for Mr Peter Bone","Wellingborough","Mr Peter Bone","55253"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647327","Department for Exiting the European Union","false","2016-12-01","<p>To date, the Department for Exiting the European Union has utilised the services of eight consultancy firms on a pro bono or nominal basis.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Consultancy Service Provider</p></td><td><p>Services provided</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Accenture</p></td><td><p>Policy support</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Frontier Economics</p></td><td><p>Market analysis</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>KPMG</p></td><td><p>Support Programme Management Office and departmental set-up</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Oliver Wyman</p></td><td><p>Policy support</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>McKinsey</p></td><td><p>Organisational design and assurance consultancy</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Deloitte</p></td><td><p>Internal financial planning</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>PWC</p></td><td><p>Departmental set-up and Programme Management support</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p>The department has also utilised the services of two paid secondees from the Boston Consulting Group on civil service salary levels supporting policy development.</p><p> </p>","Clwyd West","Mr David Jones","55211","2016-12-01T15:30:21.097Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647327/answer","Biography information for Mr David Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647327/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/647327/answer",,,,,"203","Exiting the European Union","Exiting the European Union","2016-11-28","Department for Exiting the European Union: Consultants","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Exiting the European Union, pursuant to the Answer of 13 October 2016 to Question 47680, if he will list the consultancy firms that his Department has utilised the services of on a pro bono or nominal (£1) basis to date.","false","Biography information for Hilary Benn","Leeds Central","Hilary Benn","55210"
