"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643776","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-12-08","<p>The £18 million fund is a ‘capacity fund’ to tackle planning issues that can cause delay and prevent builders from getting on site and starting work quickly.</p><p>It can be used to facilitate house building on all ownership and tenure models.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-12-08T15:32:50.757Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643776/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643776/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643776/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-11-24","Council Housing: Construction","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how much of the new £18 million fund to accelerate house building will be used to build council houses.","true","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL3536"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643777","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-12-07","<p>In the Autumn Statement the Chancellor announced a £1.4 billion expansion of the Shared Ownership and Affordable Homes Programme (SOAHP) 2016-21 and a relaxation of restrictions on tenure. The expanded and more flexible programme will allow providers to have the agility to quickly and effectively respond with the right products to local needs and markets. Local authorities, along with other providers, are able to bid into the programme, and so the proportion of the 40,000 starts that local authorities build will become clear through the bids that are submitted during the continuous market engagement phase.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-12-07T15:35:02.377Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643777/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643777/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643777/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-11-24","Council Housing: Construction","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many of the 40,000 affordable housing starts announced in the Autumn Statement they expect to be council houses.","true","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL3537"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643778","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-11-30","<p>The £1.8 billion is the amount of additional investment that housing associations will need to take, from lenders and through cross subsidy across schemes, in order to deliver the much needed affordable homes. As housing associations are currently classified as public corporations this investment also counts towards the fiscal aggregates.</p><p>We are taking action to enable the Office for National Statistics to reclassify housing associations to the private sector.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-11-30T13:04:21.337Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643778/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643778/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643778/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-11-24","Housing Associations: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government where the £1.8 billion of extra spending by Housing Associations from sources other than central government is coming from.","true","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL3538"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643779","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-12-08","<p>The government’s announcement of £7.2 billion to support the construction of new homes at the Autumn Statement is part of the new National Productivity Investment Fund. The Fund will add £23 billion in high-value investment from 2017/18 to 2021/22.</p><p>Within the £7.2 billion envelope, the government will provide an additional £1.4 billion to deliver an additional 40,000 affordable housing starts by 2020/21. The Autumn Statement envelope also includes borrowing by housing associations from private sector sources as a result of the additional investment. The government will also invest £1.7 billion by 2020/21 to speed up house building on public sector land. Finally, the government announced a new Housing Infrastructure Fund of £2.3 billion by 2020/21 which will deliver up to 100,000 new homes. Further details on how this fund will be allocated to local authorities will be set out in due course.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-12-08T15:33:17.953Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643779/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643779/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643779/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-11-24","Housing: Construction","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is the time period for the spending of the £7.2 billion on housing announced in the Autumn Statement.","true","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL3539"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643780","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-12-07","<p>The government’s Housing Infrastructure Fund covers £2.3 billion of new funding up to 2020/21 as part of the government’s National Productivity Investment Fund. Local authorities will be able to bid for funding for infrastructure such as new roads or utility connections (such as water, energy and internet) to unlock housing sites in high demand areas. This will support the delivery of up to 100,000 new homes. Further details on how this Fund will be allocated to local authorities will be set out in due course.</p><p> </p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-12-07T15:31:52.127Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643780/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643780/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643780/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-11-24","Housing Infrastructure Fund","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what they envisage the £2.3 billion Housing Infrastructure Fund being spent on, and over what timescale.","true","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL3540"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643781","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-12-07","<p>We have expanded the Shared Ownership and Affordable Homes Programme 2016-21 with an additional £1.4billion to deliver a further 40,000 housing starts by 2021, increasing the overall capital budget to over £7 billion. Housing Co-Operatives and others will be able to apply when the expanded programme opens to new bids early in the new-year through continuous market engagement. However, there will be no artificially imposed limit or quota on how much will be available for Housing Co-Operatives or other providers. The greater tenure flexibility we have introduced in the expanded programme will also make it easier for Co-Operatives to bid to deliver new homes.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-12-07T15:32:56.78Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643781/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643781/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643781/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-11-24","Housing: Cooperatives","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how much of the £7.2 billion housing investment announced in the Autumn Statement is earmarked for co-operative housing.","true","Biography information for Lord Kennedy of Southwark",,"Lord Kennedy of Southwark","HL3541"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643782","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-07","<p>Sir Kim Darroch took up his appointment in January 2016. In line with our approach to all US elections, the British Ambassador and his team have had extensive engagement with Mr Trump's campaign and transition teams.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-12-07T15:09:17.923Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643782/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643782/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643782/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-24","USA: Diplomatic Service","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when Sir Kim Darroch was appointed as UK Ambassador to the USA; and how many meetings he has had with the now President-Elect since he was appointed.","false","Biography information for Lord Kilclooney",,"Lord Kilclooney","HL3542"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643783","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-02","<p>The Ambassador last raised the opening of a country office for the UN Office of the High Commissioner for Human Rights in August.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-12-02T14:41:58.077Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643783/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643783/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643783/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-24","Burma: UN High Commissioner for Human Rights","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of recent events in Rakhine State, when the UK's Ambassador in Burma last discussed with the new administration there the opening of a full country office for the UN Office of the High Commissioner for Human Rights.","false","Biography information for Baroness Nye",,"Baroness Nye","HL3543"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643784","Home Office","false","2016-12-08","<p>Under section 67 of the Immigration Act 2016, the Government committed to relocating a specified number of unaccompanied child refugees from Europe. The specified number will be announced in due course.</p><p>Under the family reunion provisions of the Dublin III Regulation, unaccompanied asylum-seeking children who have family already in the UK can be transferred to the UK for consideration of their asylum claim. Between 1 January 2016 and 1 October 2016, over 140 unaccompanied asylum-seeking children in Europe have been accepted for transfer to the UK under the family reunion provisions of the Dublin Regulation, compared to fewer than 20 in 2015.</p><p>Since 10 October, we have transferred over 300 unaccompanied children to the UK from France. This includes over 80 girls, many of whom were identified as being at a high risk of sexual exploitation; and more than 200 children with close family links to the UK under the Dublin III Regulation. The Home Secretary told Parliament on 24 October that several hundred more children and young people will be brought to the UK in the coming days and weeks.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-12-08T16:28:18.41Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643784/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643784/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643784/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-24","Refugees: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they are proposing to resettle in the UK a proportion of the estimated 85,000 unaccompanied child refugees who have made asylum applications in other EU member countries.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL3544"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643785","Home Office","false","2016-12-07","<p>Unaccompanied asylum seeking and refugee children who are not reunited with family are accommodated by a local authority and the child will become legally looked-after under Section 20 of the Children Act 1989 (or equivalent devolved legislation).</p><p>This means that they will be safeguarded and have their welfare promoted in the same way as any other looked after child.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-12-07T17:49:23.01Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643785/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643785/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643785/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-24","Refugees: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how they propose to accommodate and rehabilitate future child refugees in the UK.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL3545"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643786","Department for Education","false","2016-12-01","<p>Caring for any child requires skills and dedication. Local authorities and independent fostering agencies select and prepare all foster carers for this challenging role. The Government is committed to ensuring foster carers are afforded the appropriate recognition, support and training to ensure every looked-after child receives the high-quality care they need. We have funded a range of initiatives including “Fosterline” – a helpline which provides a confidential, impartial free advice service for foster carers and potential foster carers.</p><p> </p><p>In addition, in September we commissioned the Refugee Council and ECPAT to deliver training for foster carers and support workers who are not experienced in working with unaccompanied asylum seeking or refugee children. The Government has also committed to evaluate the need for any additional training required by foster carers looking after unaccompanied children as part of our wider safeguarding strategy for unaccompanied asylum-seeking and refugee children. Further information on our safeguarding strategy can be found on the Government’s website, GOV.UK, by searching for ‘Safeguarding unaccompanied asylum-seeking and refugee children’.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-12-01T15:36:37.317Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643786/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643786/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643786/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-11-24","Refugees: Children","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to select and guide the foster parents of new child refugees.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL3546"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643787","Department of Health","false","2016-12-06","<p>The <em>Five Year Forward View for Mental Health</em> recommended that the Department and NHS England should work with the Royal College of General Practitioners and Health Education England (HEE) to ensure that by 2020 all general practitioners (GPs), including the 5,000 joining the workforce by 2020-21, receive core mental health training, and to develop a new role of GPs with an extended Scope of Practice in Mental Health, with at least 700 in practice within five years.</p><p> </p><p>HEE offers the MindEd programme to GPs, which provides a free e-learning resource including a session on obsessive compulsive disorder.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-12-06T15:31:15.297Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643787/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643787/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643787/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-24","Obsessive Compulsive Disorder","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what steps they are taking to raise GPs' awareness of obsessive compulsive disorder in order to ensure that patients are not misdiagnosed.","false","Biography information for Lord Roberts of Llandudno",,"Lord Roberts of Llandudno","HL3547"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643788","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-08","<p>Our Ambassador to Peru discussed this with the Peruvian Environment Minister on 15 August and the Energy Minister on 2 September. The Peruvian Ministry of Environment believe affected areas will take a year to recover, whereas independent scientists are of the opinion that this will take much longer and damage may be irreversible, with a direct impact on livelihoods and local economies.</p><p>The Ambassador last met indigenous communities during an official visit to Iquitos in late 2015.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-12-08T15:56:40.287Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643788/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643788/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643788/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-24","Peru: Rain Forests","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the impact of oil spills on the environment and the livelihoods of indigenous populations in the Peruvian Amazon; and what contact the UK Ambassador to Peru has had with those communities.","false","Biography information for Baroness Royall of Blaisdon",,"Baroness Royall of Blaisdon","HL3548"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643789","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-07","<p>The British Embassy in Lima works closely with the European Union Delegation and the Embassies of other EU countries to support the implementation of the EU Guidelines on Human Rights Defenders. This includes regular dialogue with human rights defenders on issues of concern, engagement with them on visits outside the capital, and participation in the EU's annual human rights defenders event.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-12-07T15:09:49.05Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643789/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643789/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643789/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-24","Peru: Human Rights","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what action is being taken to implement the European Union Guidelines on Human Rights Defenders in Peru.","false","Biography information for Baroness Royall of Blaisdon",,"Baroness Royall of Blaisdon","HL3549"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643790","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-12-08","<p>​This law was a notable step forward in protecting the rights of indigenous peoples in Peru.</p><p>Our Ambassador to Peru discussed the issue with the Peruvian Minister for Culture on 11 August. The Minister confirmed his intention to strengthen the Indigenous People's Department in his ministry to facilitate implementation of the law. We will continue to work with the Peruvian Government on this important area of activity.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-12-08T16:14:12.9Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643790/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643790/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643790/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2016-11-24","Peru: Indigenous Peoples","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what is their assessment of the implementation of the Peruvian Law on the Right of Consultation of Indigenous Peoples 2011.","false","Biography information for Baroness Royall of Blaisdon",,"Baroness Royall of Blaisdon","HL3550"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643791","Home Office","false","2016-12-08","<p>The Police National Database does not link custody images to individual crime records. Therefore this information could only be obtained through a costly and time-consuming review of all images held by forces.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-12-08T16:39:06.233Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643791/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643791/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643791/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2016-11-24","Police: Biometrics","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of how many of the 19 million custody images that are being stored on the Police National Database would have to be removed if the same retention rules that apply to DNA and fingerprints were put into place.","false","Biography information for Lord Scriven",,"Lord Scriven","HL3551"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643792","Department of Health","false","2016-12-07","<p>Many general practitioners (GPs) undertake some non-National Health Service work - such as the completion of medical forms for which they charge patients and this is accepted as being part of normal GP practice. GPs are unable to charge registered patients for appointments, and any private work should not impact on their contractual obligation to provide access to services within the core hours of 8am – 6.30pm, Monday to Friday, excluding bank holidays, to meet the reasonable needs of their patients.</p><p> </p><p><em>The National Health Service (General Medical Services – Premises Costs) Directions 2013,</em> provide, that where a third party rents part of the surgery and pays towards the running costs of the premises, this amount must be abated from the amount reimbursed by NHS England. A copy of the Directions is attached.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-12-07T16:10:09.283Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643792/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643792/answer","NHS__General_Medical_Services_-_Premises_Costs__Directions_2013.pdf","NHS__General_Medical_Services_-_Premises_Costs__Directions_2013.pdf","Directions","Directions","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643792/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2016-11-24","General Practitioners: Private Sector","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what, if any, is their policy in respect of GPs who use their NHS surgeries after hours or at lunchtimes for private consultations, while employed by a private provider.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL3552"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643793","Department for Education","false","2016-12-01","<p>Sex education is already compulsory in secondary maintained schools, and the Government is clear that all schools should make provision for high quality, age-appropriate sex and relationship education, which is a vital part of preparing young people for life in modern Britain.</p><p> </p><p>The Secretary of State agreed that we need to look again at how schools deliver high quality personal, social, health and economic education including sex and relationship education. The Government is considering all the options and will give a view in due course.</p>",,"Lord Nash",,"2016-12-01T15:37:08.8Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643793/answer","Biography information for Lord Nash","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643793/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643793/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2016-11-24","Sex and Relationship Education","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the answer by Lord Nash on 24 November, when they expect to announce a date for the introduction of statutory sex and relationship education in all state schools.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL3553"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643794","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-12-08","<p>The government has no plans to undertake a revaluation of properties.</p>",,"Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth",,"2016-12-08T15:32:29.08Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643794/answer","Biography information for Lord Bourne of Aberystwyth","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643794/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643794/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-11-24","Council Tax: Valuation","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they are planning to undertake a revaluation of properties with a view to amending council tax bands.","false","Biography information for Baroness Tonge",,"Baroness Tonge","HL3554"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643811","Attorney General","false","2016-12-02","<p>I regularly meet Ministerial colleagues to discuss important issues of common interest, including on domestic and international human rights law. I am not able to talk about any legal content of those discussions because, by convention, the fact that the Law Officers have advised or have not advised and the content of their advice must not be disclosed outside Government without their authority.</p>","South Swindon","Robert Buckland",,"2016-12-02T16:03:17.767Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643811/answer","Biography information for Robert Buckland","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643811/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643811/answer",,,,,"88","Attorney General","Attorney General","2016-11-24","Human Rights","1","House of Commons","To ask the Attorney General, what recent discussions he has had with Cabinet colleagues on the implementation of the UK's domestic and international legal obligations on human rights.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","54676"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643812","Cabinet Office","false","2016-12-01","<p>A variety of internships are undertaken across government and no central database is kept of these internships. The Civil Service Fast Stream runs a Summer (for penultimate and final year undergraduates) and Early (for first year undergraduates) Diversity Internship programme. For the summer scheme, 308 intern placements were offered in 2016 and 100 placements were offered for the early scheme. Applications are now open for the 2017 schemes</p><p> </p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-12-01T09:59:37.133Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643812/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643812/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643812/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-11-24","Government Departments: Work Experience","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many internships currently exist in all government departments.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","54796"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643813","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-11-29","<p>Ofcom has reported that in summer 2016, 88% of premises were capable of receiving speeds of more than 30Mbps. Thinkbroadband report current availability at 30Mbps for 91.42% of premises, with 92% being able to receive speeds above 24Mbps.</p>","West Suffolk","Matt Hancock","54835","2016-11-29T13:04:18.723Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643813/answer","Biography information for Matt Hancock","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643813/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643813/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2016-11-24","Broadband","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Culture, Media and Sport, what recent estimate she has made of the number of households capable of receiving 30 megabits a second.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","54820"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643814","Cabinet Office","false","2016-12-01","<p>This information is not held centrally within the Cabinet Office. The information requested could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p><p> </p>","Ipswich","Ben Gummer",,"2016-12-01T09:58:35.883Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643814/answer","Biography information for Ben Gummer","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643814/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643814/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2016-11-24","Government Departments: Personnel Management","1","House of Commons","To ask the Minister for the Cabinet Office, how many people employed in human resources roles in the civil service have (a) prior experience and (b) qualifications in human resources.","false","Biography information for Louise Haigh","Sheffield, Heeley","Louise Haigh","54840"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643815","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-29","<p>The Government published analysis showing the impact of taxation, welfare and public spending decisions taken at Autumn Statement 2016. This distributional analysis used HM Treasury’s microsimulation model.</p><p> </p><p>This analysis can be found at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/autumn-statement-2016-documents" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/publications/autumn-statement-2016-documents</a></p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-11-29T17:52:14.66Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643815/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643815/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643815/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-11-24","Public Expenditure","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, if he will publish the full analysis undertaken by his Department's tax and benefit microsimulation model on the Autumn Statement 2016.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","54874"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643816","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-11-29","<p>The West Midlands Combined Authority will receive a total of £70 million grant funding in 2017/18. This is separate to the funding that local authorities receive individually and is broken down as follows:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>(a) Adult education: £Nil</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(b) Transport: £33.5 million</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(c) Work and Health Programme: £Nil</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(d) Business support: £Nil</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>(e) Any other sources of funding by grant: £36.5 million (Gain share)</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Brigg and Goole","Andrew Percy",,"2016-11-29T16:42:52.14Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643816/answer","Biography information for Andrew Percy","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643816/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643816/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-11-24","West Midlands Combined Authority: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, how much grant funding West Midlands Combined Authority will receive in financial year 2017-18 for (a) adult education, (b) transport, (c) the Work and Health Programme, (d) business support and (e) any other sources of funding by grant.","false","Biography information for Jack Dromey","Birmingham, Erdington","Jack Dromey","54823"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643817","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-29","<p>As announced by the Chancellor of the Exchequer at the Autumn Statement, the Midlands Engine strategy will be published shortly.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-11-29T17:40:23.33Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643817/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643817/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643817/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-11-24","Regional Planning and Development: Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when the Government plans to publish the Midlands Engine strategy.","false","Biography information for Jack Dromey","Birmingham, Erdington","Jack Dromey","54824"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643818","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-29","<p>The Autumn Statement announced that the government will award £1.8 billion to Local Enterprise Partnerships across England. LEPs in the Midlands will receive a total of £392 million. A further £556 million will go to the North of England, £151 million to the East of England, £492 million to London and the South East, and £191 million to the South West. Awards to individual LEPs will be announced in the coming months.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-11-29T17:42:01.237Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643818/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643818/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643818/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-11-24","Local Enterprise Partnerships: West Midlands","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when he plans to publish the amount of funding the Greater Birmingham and Solihull Local Enterprise Partnership will receive under the Growth Deal announced in paragraph 3.49 of the Autumn Statement 2016.","false","Biography information for Jack Dromey","Birmingham, Erdington","Jack Dromey","54826"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643819","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-30","<p>Air Passenger Duty (APD) is a tax levied on airlines with respect to any passengers departing from a UK airport. Airlines aggregate their full APD liabilities when making payments, and there is no requirement on them to attribute this to particular flights. The government does not believe that any benefits from reforming the reporting process would outweigh the additional administrative burdens on taxpayers.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-11-30T16:59:21.85Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643819/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643819/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643819/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-11-24","Air Passenger Duty","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what his policy is on reforming the reporting of air passenger duty to attribute that duty to each airport.","false","Biography information for Jim McMahon","Oldham West and Royton","Jim McMahon","54789"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643820","HM Treasury","false","2016-12-02","<p>The £170 million flood defence and resilience funding announced at Autumn Statement 2016 is an allocation from the £700m announced in the March 2016 Budget.</p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-12-02T11:17:32.757Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643820/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643820/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643820/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-11-24","Flood Control: Capital Investment","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, with reference to paragraph 3.25 of the Autumn Statement 2016, whether that investment in flood defence and resilience measures is in addition to the investment in flood defences announced in the March 2016 Budget.","false","Biography information for Mary Creagh","Wakefield","Mary Creagh","54791"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643821","HM Treasury","false","2016-12-01","<p>The government will publish further details of the terms of the NS&amp;I Investment Bonds in due course, and with sufficient time for prospective customers to be informed ahead of the product going on sale in spring 2017. The final rate will be confirmed at the 2017 spring budget.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2016-12-01T16:14:45.317Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643821/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643821/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643821/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-11-24","National Savings Bonds","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when he plans to publish the full terms of his planned Investment Guaranteed Growth Bonds.","false","Biography information for Helen Goodman","Bishop Auckland","Helen Goodman","54792"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643822","HM Treasury","false","2016-12-02","<p>Details of the number of employees receiving Employee Shareholder Status shares in the tax year 2013 to 2014, the latest year for which data is available, are in Table 14.9 contained in the Capital Gains Tax Statistics published on Gov.uk - <a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/statistics/capital-gains-tax-statistics" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/statistics/capital-gains-tax-statistics</a>. Breakdown by geographical areas is not available.</p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-12-02T13:28:43.837Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643822/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643822/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643822/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-11-24","Employee Ownership","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what estimate his Department has made of the number of participants in the Employee Shareholder Status scheme in (a) Rutherglen and Hamilton West constituency, (b) Scotland and (c) the UK.","false","Biography information for Margaret Ferrier","Rutherglen and Hamilton West","Margaret Ferrier","54693"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643823","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-30","<p>The UK insurance industry is the largest in Europe and the third largest in the world. The government is aware of the important contribution of insurance to the nation’s economy and it is also keen to ensure the industry remains competitive as the United Kingdom leaves the European Union. The steps we will take in the EU negotiations will be to achieve the best possible deal for the financial services sector as a whole.</p><p> </p><p>In the meantime, the government continues to improve competitiveness and encourage growth in the sector. For example, as announced in the Autumn Statement, the government is consulting on draft regulations which will introduce a competitive regulatory and tax regime for Insurance Linked Securities in the UK. The regulations are designed to allow the UK to compete in this innovative area and will enhance our position as a global insurance hub.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2016-11-30T16:24:13.463Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643823/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643823/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643823/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-11-24","Insurance: Competition","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what steps he is taking as part of the negotiations for the UK to leave the EU to improve the competitiveness of the UK insurance industry.","false","Biography information for Mr Chris Leslie","Nottingham East","Chris Leslie","54847"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643824","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-29","<p>This Government is committed to tackling the root causes of disadvantage and poverty, and not just the symptoms. The Government have introduced two new measures that will drive real action on worklessness and educational attainment – the two areas that we know can make the biggest difference to disadvantaged children and their families. The Government will publish a report on these measures by March 2017.</p><p> </p><p>HM Treasury ministers and officials have meetings with a wide variety of organisations in the public and private sectors as part of the process of policy development and delivery.</p><p> </p><p>Details of ministerial and permanent secretary meetings with external organisations on departmental business are published on a quarterly basis at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/hmt-ministers-meetings-hospitality-gifts-and-overseas-travel" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/hmt-ministers-meetings-hospitality-gifts-and-overseas-travel</a></p><p> </p><p>The Government continues to perform all its legal duties with respect to equalities.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","54872","2016-11-29T17:52:49.567Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643824/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643824/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643824/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-11-24","Children: Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what discussions he has had with external organisations on the effect of the Autumn Statement 2016 on child poverty.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","54871"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643825","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-29","<p>This Government is committed to tackling the root causes of disadvantage and poverty, and not just the symptoms. The Government have introduced two new measures that will drive real action on worklessness and educational attainment – the two areas that we know can make the biggest difference to disadvantaged children and their families. The Government will publish a report on these measures by March 2017.</p><p> </p><p>HM Treasury ministers and officials have meetings with a wide variety of organisations in the public and private sectors as part of the process of policy development and delivery.</p><p> </p><p>Details of ministerial and permanent secretary meetings with external organisations on departmental business are published on a quarterly basis at:</p><p><a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/hmt-ministers-meetings-hospitality-gifts-and-overseas-travel" target="_blank">https://www.gov.uk/government/collections/hmt-ministers-meetings-hospitality-gifts-and-overseas-travel</a></p><p> </p><p>The Government continues to perform all its legal duties with respect to equalities.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke","54871","2016-11-29T17:52:49.647Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643825/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643825/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643825/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-11-24","Children: Poverty","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the effect of the Autumn Statement 2016 on child poverty.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","54872"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643826","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-29","The Government is determined to ensure that the NHS is focused on delivering for patients this winter. The NHS does extensive preparation for winter every year and takes such preparations very seriously. This year, for example, NHS England has made provision for winter preparedness funding of £400m, and has launched with Public Health England a national campaign to help guide patients and the public on how to keep healthy and safe during the winter season. Flu vaccinations have also begun earlier than in recent years, with over 5 million jabs having already been administered. As part of this, for the first time ever, children in year 3 will be offered the flu vaccine – meaning an additional 600,000 children will be protected this winter, making this the largest flu vaccination programme to date. The Department of Health is also working with the NHS and social care leaders to deliver the A&amp;E Improvement Plan and ensure that appropriate staffing levels are in place throughout the Christmas and New Year periods. Additionally, the Cold Weather Plan brings together national and local government, NHS England and the social care system to reduce cold-related harm. The Government also provides Winter Fuel Payments, Cold Weather Payments and the Warm Home Discount to help the elderly and vulnerable keep warm over winter. More broadly, as the Chancellor of the Exchequer outlined at the Autumn Statement, the Government remains committed to the spending plans for the NHS outlined at the Spending Review 2015. The NHS will receive £10 billion a year more in government funding by 2020-21 than in 2014-15. This is a significant investment and will help to ease the pressures on hospitals and GPs.","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-11-29T17:41:11.46Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643826/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643826/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643826/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-11-24","Death: Weather","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what assessment he has made of the effect of the Autumn Statement 2016 on excess winter deaths.","false","Biography information for Dan Jarvis","Barnsley Central","Dan Jarvis","54873"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643827","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-30","<p>This question has been passed on to the Financial Conduct Authority (FCA). The FCA will reply to directly to the Honourable member by letter. A copy of the letter will be placed in the Library of the House.</p><p> </p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2016-11-30T16:35:51.177Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643827/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643827/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643827/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-11-24","Credit: Fraud","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many criminal prosecutions there were against illegal consumer credit providers by the Financial Conduct Authority in (a) 2014-15 and (b) 2015-16.","false","Biography information for Mr Laurence Robertson","Tewkesbury","Mr Laurence Robertson","54860"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643828","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-29","<p>The Chancellor will visit constituencies across the UK in due course. All his visits are recorded in the transparency data published on gov.uk.</p>","Brighton, Kemptown","Simon Kirby",,"2016-11-29T14:53:38.077Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643828/answer","Biography information for Simon Kirby","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643828/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643828/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-11-24","Domestic Visits: Copeland","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when he next plans to visit Copeland constituency.","false","Biography information for Mr Jamie Reed","Copeland","Mr Jamie Reed","54674"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643829","HM Treasury","false","2016-12-01","<p>The former Chancellor commissioned the London South Coast Rail Corridor Study in 2015, which looks at the region’s rail transport needs broadly. The Study considers the case for investment in the Brighton Main Line, re-opening the Lewes-Uckfield line, as well as the ‘BML2’ concept, for a new mainline to London. The Government will publish the London and South Coast Rail Corridor Study, and its response to the recommendations, in due course.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-12-01T16:08:57.957Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643829/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643829/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643829/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-11-24","Railways: South East","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, when he plans to publish the London and South Coast Rail Corridor Study; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Caroline Lucas","Brighton, Pavilion","Caroline Lucas","54670"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643830","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-12-02","<p>As of 31 December 2014, 4,690 businesses were in receipt of mandatory rural rate relief. The Department does not hold data on how many of these businesses are pubs, so it is not possible to estimate the number of pubs that will benefit from the extension of rural rate relief. As announced at Autumn Statement we are doubling the level of rural rate relief. Eligible pubs and petrol stations with a rateable value of £12,500 or below will benefit from 100% relief.</p>","Nuneaton","Mr Marcus Jones",,"2016-12-02T14:58:15.82Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643830/answer","Biography information for Mr Marcus Jones","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643830/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643830/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2016-11-24","Public Houses: Non-domestic Rates","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, if he will make an estimate of the number of pubs that will benefit from the extension of rural rates relief.","false","Biography information for Graham Evans","Weaver Vale","Graham Evans","54675"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643831","HM Treasury","false","2016-11-29","<p>At the end of every tax year HM Revenue and Customs (HMRC) electronically reviews all individual PAYE records to see whether or not the correct amount of tax and National Insurance Contributions for the year has been paid. Where there is an under or overpayment, HMRC notifies the individual through issuing form P800.</p><p> </p><p>For 2012-13, of the 45.3 million accounts reviewed, there were 5.65 million P800 forms issued. HMRC does not hold comparable figures for the tax years prior to 2012-13.</p><p> </p>","Battersea","Jane Ellison",,"2016-11-29T17:08:05.687Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643831/answer","Biography information for Jane Ellison","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643831/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643831/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-11-24","Taxation: Forms","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, how many P800 adjustments were issued to individual taxpayers to correct for an over or under-payment of income tax in (a) 2010-11, (b) 2011-12 and (c) 2012-13.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","54672"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643832","HM Treasury","false","2016-12-01","<p>The government agreed a mayoral devolution deal with the West Midlands on 17 November 2015, which will give the West Midlands Mayoral Combined Authority additional powers and funding. Discussions on implementation, between the combined authority and government, are ongoing.</p><p> </p><p>As the government announced at the Autumn Statement, it will continue to work towards a second devolution deal with the West Midlands Combined Authority. It will also give mayoral combined authorities powers to borrow for their new functions, which will allow them to invest in economically productive infrastructure, subject to agreeing a borrowing cap with HM Treasury.</p><p> </p>","South West Hertfordshire","Mr David Gauke",,"2016-12-01T16:07:37.493Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643832/answer","Biography information for Mr David Gauke","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643832/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/643832/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2016-11-24","West Midlands Combined Authority: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask Mr Chancellor of the Exchequer, what discussions he has had with the West Midlands Combined Authority on granting that Authority power to fund non-transport infrastructure projects.","false","Biography information for Ian Austin","Dudley North","Ian Austin","54685"
